{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3a7dd451-960b-46a7-86ea-5803d53b5220","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` only tells the page not to inset content for safe areas — but there are typically two other things you also need:\n\n**1. Hide the Shell/NavigationPage nav bar** (if applicable):\n\n```xml\n<!-- If using Shell -->\n<ContentPage Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n             SafeAreaEdges=\"None\" ...>\n\n<!-- If using NavigationPage -->\n<ContentPage NavigationPage.HasNavigationBar=\"False\"\n             SafeAreaEdges=\"None\" ...>\n```\n\n**2. On Android, opt into edge-to-edge drawing.** The app won't draw behind system bars unless you tell it to. In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:\n\n```csharp\nusing AndroidX.Core.View;\n\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n}\n```\n\n> On Android 15 (API 35+) edge-to-edge is enforced automatically, but for older targets you need this.\n\n**3. Use `Aspect=\"AspectFill\"`** on the Image so it fills the available space:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n             SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"\n             xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n           Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n           VerticalOptions=\"Fill\"\n           HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThe combination of all three — no nav bar, edge-to-edge on Android, and `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` — should give you a truly full-bleed image.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"526a6412-ad68-406d-8f64-d736035f0a5a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is working on a .NET MAUI app targeting .NET 10 and wants an image to go edge-to-edge, behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is a .NET MAUI question about edge-to-edge/full-screen display. Let me think about what's needed:\n\n1. **`SafeAreaEdges`** - This is a property that was introduced in .NET MAUI to control safe area insets. Setting it to `\"None\"` should tell the page not to respect any safe area edges, but there may be more to it.\n\n\n2. On Android, the system bars (status bar and navigation bar) need to be handled separately—newer Android versions default to edge-to-edge, but the window might need explicit configuration to draw behind them. On iOS, safe area insets are the main concern. The solution likely involves platform-specific settings beyond just the XAML property, possibly through native configuration or platform-specific code. `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` handles the MAUI side, but on Android I need to account for platform-specific edge-to-edge setup—either through `WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows()` for older versions or relying on the default behavior in Android 15+. iOS should be covered by the safe area setting, though there might be additional configuration needed depending on the specific layout requirements. Setting up the Android platform code...\n\nThe core issues are likely the Shell or NavigationPage adding a navigation bar on top, Android not drawing behind system bars, and the Image needing `AspectFill` to properly fill the space. I should give a focused answer covering these three points.","outputTokens":1532,"requestId":"100D:1E6A:607D242:6847B82:69FD36EE"},"id":"f47107c6-bc7e-4a59-9ac2-3d60b5d9ada6","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:06:23.585Z","parentId":"9bb8709c-c9e6-4855-81a4-bc96750524e7"}
